Perspectives for Sino-American Relations 2019
NEW YORK – In 2018, the new and increasingly unpredictable dynamics of Sino-American relations unsettled wide parts of Asia.
A year earlier, US President Donald Trump returned from his particularly grandiose "State Visit Plus" to Beijing, from which China had hoped that Trump's anti-Chinese campaign rhetoric would finally be a thing of the past.
Twelve months later, China and the United States are entangled in a trade war, and the Trump administration has replaced the US "strategic engagement" in China with "strategic competition."
Adding to this, the US, European, and Chinese economies and markets were booming a year earlier.
There is great uncertainty in the financial markets today, with growth slowing down in China and Europe and higher interest rates starting to take effect in America.
The uncertainty about the future development of nuclear talks with North Korea also clouds the picture.
So what are the prospects for US-China relations in 2019?
It is likely that an agreement on the reduction of the bilateral trade deficit and on the import decisions China will make will be reached by March.
An agreement on tariff reductions is also possible by then, although the complexity of the issue could extend the targeted timeframe.
If one tariff after another were negotiated, a year could pass by.
If Chinese economic reformers, however, adopt a more drastic approach by gradually pledging to abolish all tariffs and asking Americans to do the same, a faster result could be achieved.
This would, however, run counter to Chinese trade officials who have been trained for decades to give little, let alone everything, all at once.
The reform of the so-called forced technology transfer should be relatively uncomplicated.
Nevertheless, reform is something different from the way contractual agreements might be interpreted in practice, even if there are no specific provisions on technology transfer.
The protection of intellectual property is however extremely problematic.
Earlier agreements made under the administration of President Barack Obama could be reaffirmed once again.
Enforcement or legal action in cases of violation of intellectual property rights remains a hopeless endeavor.
A possible mechanism would be to subject relevant agreements between Chinese and foreign companies to international commercial arbitration courts based in Singapore or Switzerland, which are specifically entrusted with the enforcement of intellectual property protection.
If China raises objections, it could develop its own international commercial arbitration procedure based in China.
In order to do so, however, it would have to call on qualified foreigners to join its arbitration panel in order to strengthen international credibility.
No one has confidence in Chinese trade courts.
In order to meet its own domestic reform needs, China must move towards completely independent trade and civil chambers within its judicial system, even if the criminal chamber remains under political control.
American concerns regarding state subsidies under China's "Made in China 2025" strategy will hardly be alleviated.
The fact is that all countries provide a certain level of state support to their domestic technology sectors, even though this level is highest in China.
Even if we were to prescribe a maximum level of state support for a particular company, it would be difficult to assess compliance.
I am not confident that there will be an agreement reached in this area.
Perhaps America must simply outmaneuver China by increasing public investments in research and development in the fields of information technology and biotechnology.
We should also not rule out the possibility that China may offer tariff reforms to the rest of the international community.
China might, over time, decide to take this drastic step not only with the United States, but with all member states of the World Trade Organization, to agree on tariff-free trade.
In this way, China would present itself with a nearly irresistible opportunity to position itself as a promoter of global free trade and to curb the trend towards protectionism.
As part of such a shift, China could request the member states of the Trans-Pacific Partnership (TPP) free trade agreement to join, in order to outmaneuver the United States (which exited the free trade agreement as one of Trump's first official actions) in the Asia-Pacific region.
China can be remarkably nimble when it discovers a political opening and market access.
The negotiations would be difficult, but Japan's reservations regarding China's accession to the TPP have decreased since the recent visit of Prime Minister Shinzo Abe to Beijing.
Considering the central strategic challenges in its relationship with the United States, China is likely to be committed in 2019 to general foreign and security policy to resolve conflicts in its relations with other countries.
In relations with Japan, there is already a certain normalization.
Recent data from Japan's coast guard indicates a significant reduction in Chinese incursions into the territory of the Senkaku/Diaoyu Islands in the East China Sea.
China also aims to reduce tensions with the Association of Southeast Asian Nations over the South China Sea by accelerating negotiations on a "Code of Conduct."
Additionally, China is likely to have a more relaxed relationship with India following the bilateral summit in Wuhan in April.
And China could begin to moderate its stance toward Taiwan, considering the electoral defeat suffered by the Democratic Progressive Party, which supports Taiwan's independence, in the recent local and regional elections last month.
This would naturally change radically if the USA continue with further significant weapons sales to Taiwan, which is likely.
Incidents at sea with the USA in the South China Sea continue to occur, and the conflict could escalate if the USA more forcefully emphasize their stance on "freedom of navigation" next year.
Across all of Eurasia, China will continue to implement its major project, the "New Silk Road."
However, in recent months, the initiative has not generated as much political hype in China.
Among Chinese officials, discussions are already taking place about revising certain modalities, following Sri Lanka's handover of the Hambantota Port to China, which triggered negative reactions and raised concerns regarding the long-term financial viability of the New Silk Road.
2019 could therefore see fewer triumphant reports on the New Silk Road to be heard.
In addition, China is likely to consolidate and expand its role within the United Nations and existing Bretton Woods institutions, rather than highlight new institutions of international political action.
It is likely to continue as a new defender of the WHO and maintain its stance on global climate change, as agreed in the Paris Climate Agreement of 2015.
More cautious representatives of China's foreign policy establishment believe it would be better to focus on existing mechanisms of the global rule-based system, especially when the US consistently shows contempt.
While China tries to restore its relations with the US and reduce tensions in its relations with other countries, its leadership is likely to use the year 2019 to form a well-informed opinion on the future of US policy: the consequences of the Mueller investigation for Trump and his administration, and whether a new president in 2020 (or earlier) would change the new US strategy in any way.
Although they have already come to the conclusion that America's stance towards China has fundamentally changed, they are still uncertain about the exact form this change takes and whether a fundamental strategic shift (as opposed to tactical measures) is warranted.
